-- Stock funds worldwide post $7 bln outflows - BofA
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Fri May 23, 2014 09:44AM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, May 23 (Reuters) - Fund investors worldwide pulled $7 billion out of stock funds in the week ended May 21, reversing the prior week's inflows of $11 billion, data from a Bank of America Merrill Lynch Global Research report showed on Friday.

Funds that specialize in U.S. stocks posted $10.9 billion in outflows, reversing the prior week's $6 billion in inflows, according to data from the report, which also cited data from fund-tracker EPFR Global.  Emerging markets stock funds attracted $1 billion in new cash, marking their second straight week of inflows.  Bond funds attracted $5.9 billion in inflows, marking their 11th straight week of inflows. Low-risk money market funds attracted $10 billion in inflows, reversing $4.9 billion in outflows over the prior week.